      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA274-kiḷavi">itu tōḻi paruvamāṟupaṭṭatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante disagreed with the season.</p>
        </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA274">
<l>            neṭuvāṉ miṉṉik kuṟuntuḷit talaiip</l>
<l>            paṭumaḻai poḻinta pakuvāyk kuṉṟat</l>
<l>            tuḻaimā ṉampiṇai tīṇṭali ṉiḻaimakaḷ</l>
<l>            poṉcey kāci ṉoṇpaḻan tāaṅ</l>
<l>            kumiḻtalai mayaṅkiya kuṟumpa latta </l>
<l>            memmoṭu varutiyō pomma lōtiyeṉak</l>
<l>            kūṟiṉṟu muṭaiyarō maṟṟē vēṟupaṭ</l>
<l>            ṭirumpuli vaḻaṅkuñ cōlaip</l>
<l>            peruṅkal vaippiṟ curaṉiṟan tōrē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Didn’t he use to say<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kūṟiṉṟu-um uṭaiyar</term>: supposedly this idiom (literally "he possesses saying") expresses an iterative or even habitual quality, here to be understood as past tense because of the context. Is there an additional nuance in the -<term xml:lang="ta">um</term> added to <term xml:lang="ta">kūṟiṉṟu</term>? The particle -<term xml:lang="ta">ōmaṟṟē</term> certainly gives the question a strong rhetoric flavour ("he definitely had said so"), which is rendered in the translation by way of negation.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">“will you come with us, [you of] thick hair,</l>
<l rend="indent2">on the short many routes confused<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kumiḻ talai mayaṅkiya</term>: how to understand this phrase? I feel it might refer to the tree tops closing over the small path, but T.V.G. for one explains that it refers to fruit falling from the trees on the route.</note> with the tops of Kumiḻ trees,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the fruits bright as golden beads from a jewel[-wearing] woman</l>
<l rend="indent">are spreading, when the pretty doe of the male deer touches [the trees],<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tīṇṭaliṉ</term>: this is explained by T.V.G. as the doe rubbing her back against the tree. The oblique of the verbal noun tends to go along with temporal or causal meaning, but here one might also consider the possibility of a final sense (i.e. an oblique for a dative): "for the doe to seize".</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">on the split-mouthed hills on which coming rain has flown,</l>
<l rend="indent3">the long sky having flashed [and] offered small drops?”,</l>
<l>– the one who traversed the desert of stony regions</l>
<l rend="indent">with groves where the big tiger roams, having changed [its mood]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vēṟupaṭṭu</term> here probably refers to the tiger that is suddenly seized by hunger and goes to hunt. T.V.G. considers also connecting it with <term xml:lang="ta">vaippiṉ</term>, i.e. regions that have become different from those at home (which seems a little more farfetched).</note>?</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
